From Murudai on codeplex
http://monogame.codeplex.com/discussions/395280#post912159

I do notice however that pausing/resuming SoundEffects didn't work. In SoundEffectInstance.cs inside the Resume() function it just had "Play();", but I fixed it by replacing that with: 

if(hasSourceId)
{
     controller.PlaySound(soundBuffer);
}
soundState = SoundState.Playing;

Version: 2.5.1
File: MonoGame.Framework\iOS\GamerServices\Guide.cs
Method: ShowMessageBox
Line: 247

When this method returns, the return value of BeginShowMessageBox (IAsyncResult.IsCompleted) will have the value true. And because ShowMessageBox returned before UIAlertView disappears, there is almost noway to know when the user made a choose.

My fix is insert the following code in line 277:

while (alert.Visible) {
    Thread.Sleep(1);
}

If you look at my code carefully (where I insert this loop), you'll notice that this loop is NOT on the UI thread, but an async handler which directly associated to the IAsyncResult get from BeginShowMessageBox. Only when this handler returns, IAsyncResult.IsCompleted will be set to true. So my way is block this handler until the message box dismissed. Of course a better wait mechanism is needed (like mutex), however, it's a quick fix, and can fix the problem.
